qx||cs|6|fp|1|ht|a|at|^-{          SUIT RESPONSES          }
^-|ht|c|fp||at|^b@2What about actions other than a pass or redouble?  Let's start with a minor-suit opening such as:|
HT|d|va|4|cs|6|at|^B{|ia|1cx?|at|}|ht|d|va|4|at|^m{|ia|1dx?|at|}|
PG| ***** 8 ***** |


ht|g|at|^b@2What if East bids a suit? Usually, he will have less than 10 HCP (because he could redouble with 10 or more HCP)--but he actually could have more than 10 (sorry if that is confusing). For example, with:|
pg| ***** 9 ***** |


ht|i|at|^b|ih|pSA K 8 6 5H3DQ J 8 6C 6 5 4,|ht|i|at|^K@2 I would bid 1@S over the double. I'd rather start to describe my suits than to redouble and risk the auction getting too high. After I bid 1@S to show my spades, I'll do something later to show my strength.|
PG| ***** 10 ***** |


at| If instead I held, say,|
ht|k|at|^k|ih|pSA Q 7 6HK QDJ t 9 8CT 4 3,|ht|l|at|^s@2I could redouble and hope to penalize the opponents.|
PG| ***** 11 ***** |


ht|p|at|^B@2So, when East responds with a suit bid instead of redoubling are his bids forcing? |
PG| ***** 12 ***** |


AT|Most players treat 1-level suit bids as forcing. I want to be able to bid 1@S on the hand above left and not worry that partner will pass! A 1NT response after a double shows 6-9, balanced. |
PG| ***** 13 ***** |


at|What about bids on the 2-level after a double? Let's looks at these two auctions:|
ht|s|cs|6|at|^B{|ia|1hx2c|at|}|ht|s|at|^m{|ia|1sx2h|at|}|
PG| ***** 14 ***** |


ht|v|at|^B@2Most agree that 2-level bids after a double are natural and NOT forcing.  Since you can redouble with 10 HCP, a 2-level response is assumed to be less than 10 HCP. For example, on the first auction, East could have this hand:|
ht|w|va|4|at|^B|IH|pS4 2H4 2D7 6 5CA Q J 9 8 7 |
PG| ***** 15 ***** |


HT|x|AT|^jand on  the second have this hand:|ht|w|va|4|AT|^r|IH|P S7HK Q T 9 7 6DJ 5 4 C9 8 6|
PG| ***** 16 ***** |


