qx||cs|6|fp|1|ht|a|at|^-{          SUMMARY OF MOST COMMON AGREEMENTS           
AFTER TAKEOUT DOUBLE}
^-|ht|c|fp||at|^b@2^*B

PASS= WEAK  (Usually)

REDOUBLE = 10+ HCP

ONE-LEVEL SUIT BIDS = Natural, Forcing one round (Usually less than 10, but could have more)

TWO-LEVEL SUIT BIDS (not jumps) = Natural, Not Forcing (Less than 10)^*N|
PG| ***** 19 ***** |


NT||
%%%%%%
qx||cs|6|fp|1|ht|a|at|^-{          ADVANCED          }
^-|ht|c|fp||cp|8|AT|^B@2^*BLarry Cohen: ^*N|cp||at|Surely, there are other ways to play. Many tournament players use transfers after the double (see my humbling story on this |CP|1|AT|^*Hhttps://www.larryco.com/bridge-learning-center/detail/77^*N|CP||AT|).|
PG| ***** 20 ***** |


AT|

Also, most experienced players use 2NT as conventional. The most common meaning is "JORDAN" -- it shows a limit raise or better (this is typically used only after a major-suit opening).|
PG| ***** 21 ***** |


AT| So, in this auction|
ht|h|cs|6|at|^B{|ia|1hx2n|at|}|
ht|k|at|^b@22NT would be bid with this hand: |ht|j|at|^j|ih|pSK QHK Q 3DT 9 8 7 6CJ 4 2|
PG| ***** 22 ***** |


AT|

^b@2When using this method, a redouble of 1@H or 1@S surely denies 3-card support (else you'd respond 2NT). There are many other expert treatments available after a takeout double.|
pg| ***** 23 ***** |


NT||
