qx||cs|6|fp|1|ht|a|at|^-{          APPROACH BY HOWARD SCHUTZMAN            
AFTER TAKEOUT DOUBLES}
^-|ht|E|fp||AT|^B@2^*BMM: What Cohen recommends over takeout doubles is very standard, and it is fine if you choose to play it. But Howard finds that many students find Cohen's suggested treatment somewhat confusing. Cohen says that if you bid a new suit at the 1-level that is forcing but if you bid a new suit at the 2-level it is not forcing. That seems very counter intuitive to Howard.|
PG| ***** 24 ***** |


AT|

What Howard suggests is that any bid other than redouble or 2NT denies 10 points and is not forcing. Thus 1@D-dbl-1@S is not forcing. Nor is 1@D-dbl-2@C. The only way to force and show 10+ points is to redouble or bid 2NT. 2NT is "Jordan" showing a limit raise or better in opener's suit.|
PG| ***** 25 ***** |


AT|

One other point. In Cohen's example, he makes a Jordan 2NT bid with 3-card support to show a limit raise. That is not standard. Many people play that 2NT guarantees 4-card support. With 3-card support you redouble and raise to 3 later.^*N|
pg| ***** 26 ***** |


